title: M3D fan holder for overheating printhead

description.text:
When I got my printer it worked fairly well. But after a time the print quality went down and then prints stopped extruding in the middle of the print. After a lot of trial and error and some help from support, I did a test with the print cover off and a household fan pointing at the printer. This allowed a nearly perfect print.
So what was happening was the print and print head were too hot. Maybe my fan was malfunctioning, or maybe there was a design flaw. Inspired by others I decided to move my fan to the front of the printer head. I had tried to replace the fan in the bottom of the head, but the space is really too small and it does not cool the extruder enough. In fact the fan was hitting my work as it was printing. If you put it in too high, it rubs against the X-shaft. Not a good design.
So I decided to build a custom cover and see if I can have a permanent mount for the fan in the front where it can cool the cold end of the extruder. But the print was still getting too hot, or staying too hot and the print quality was low. So I added a new piece to direct to fan exhaust down to the print area. I also taped the vents on the top so that the air was drawn in where the fan used to be. (the fan is blowing out of the cover; the logo faces out.)
I am getting really good prints and would say that this is a fix. The one issue I had was that the head moves to the right and left all the way so there is no room to run a 'vent' down below the bottom of the print head. But making the vents point toward the work area and keeping them above the gantry seems to do the trick. 
The fan just fits in the slot. It requires some pressure to get it seated.

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1 is best the tolerances are tight

Infill:

high to solid

Notes: Print the cover standing up and be patient when removing the support material. If you print it laying down the interior will be too rough to fit the fan into. You do not want to rely on bridging for this critical part. The fan cover-deflector can be printed without much support material needed if you print it on its back tipped backwards a bit. The 'horns' will have support material but you can pull it out carefully. See the attached images for printing orientation. Print this on your M3D with the existing print head cover off and with a fan pointing at the print head and print area.

NOTES This will limit the print area slightly. So the .4mm test strip will not print without the outer cover removed. So be careful. Also always be sure that the insulating cover is over the tip of the print head. The printer will not work if it has slid up the extruder tube. The original fan slides into the 'pocket' and this goes on like the original cover. The orientation of the fan is critical. One side is just the rotating blades and hub; and the other is 'protected.' I designed small spacers in the model to hold the corners of the 'open' side back so the blades can turn freely. If the fan is reversed the fan will not be able to spin. The logo for the fan should face out like in the picture. Also the air direction needs to be this way so the tubes are blowing, not sucking.

title: Smooth rod / shaft collar from a drilled out M8 nut

description.text:
This is part of an audit of the Prusa Mendel to improve stiffness and reliability.
Other byproducts of those concerns: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:11017
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10994
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15606 There is ancestry for this thing in Thingiverse, as a case for including a drilled out and tapped M5 nut to secure a pulley on a motor shaft has already been published. Cannot happen to find that design right now.
  • This method addresses concerns of slippage along smooth rods: the trapped nuts on the idler and motor ends of some of the Mendel x-end designs are held by very few layers of plastic. This drastically limits the pressure one can appply to fix in place the smooth rods. Symptoms might include the need to frequently adjust / re-tension the x axis belt. Some designs address this by closing the rod channel ends, but rod length may then be an issue.
    • Alternative solutions dealing with plastic: to significantly increase the number of layers under the trapped nuts; a printed collar piece like http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2454 (but less pressure can be applied with that one); bolted brackets (like Selis Mendel), closing out the ends of the rods channels (but rod length issues may arise then); commercial shaft collars (expensive!), etc.
  • This low cost solution will allow you to tighten and secure the smooth rods with significant pressure. To secure a Prusa Mendel's X rods you'll need to prepare 4 of those. Can come handy in many other situations.
    • Note: I drilled them at 180 degrees for expediency, but have learned since then that the optimal solution would be 90 degrees between the screws. drilling the center of faces 120 degrees apart might be an acceptable compromise.

• you'll need a stationary drill (drill press), a center punch, 8mm and 2.5 mm drills, an M3 tap, M8 nuts, m3x6 (or similar) bolts, a metal file
  • drill out the nut's center and apply 5-20 circular file strokes until the nut fits snugly the 8 mm smooth rod
  • punch the center of two nut's sides 120 dregrees apart
  • change to the 2.5 mm drill and drill the nut's sides
  • Tap those holes to M3
  • File the metal scrapes and adjust the collars on the rods. Tighten ad lib.

A pre-assembled, expandable sea-urchin birdhouse - perfect for your growing flock. Prints without support.   
This bird house looks like a spikey sea urchin and the entrance can be adjusted for tiny birds, e.g. wrens or gold crests, up to huge ones, e.g. golden eagles (maybe a bit hopeful).  Each of the twelve "leaves" is hinged on to a circular base and should print pre-assembled and ready to go.  
There's a hole in the middle to screw it to a tree...  
The idea for this came from a stainless steel steamer that unfolds like a flower.

Print on your favourite 3D printer - but not too small for the hinges to work. From Emmett's advice, PLA is a better choice than ABS (which may warp). It was printed on our Replicator in ABS using Makerware's "Low" settings - no support or raft, 5% infill, 2 shells, 0.3mm layer height, Extruder 230 deg C, Platform 110 deg C, Extrusion 100 mm/s, Travel 150 mm/s. This one is ~9cm across. As you can see from the photos, I've had fun printing (and designing) this - and there was a lot of tweaking to stop things joining. The hinged part of the leaves have been widened to make them stick to the build platform - the taller (incomplete) prints had problems with the leaves being pushed over or broken by the second extruder while printing. Finally got a successful print - using "Urchin_birdhouse_thick.STL" and the Replicator settings above. It may print better more slowly...
Once printed, it needed a tiny bit of easing with an X-Acto knife to open up the leaves; and one the hinges had flexed a few times it moved quite smoothly. Good luck printing this.

title: Rotating Outlet Cover / Child Protector - European Schuko Style

description.text: This is an outlet cover that you can use to protect your kids from the dangers of electricity. Cover consists of two parts. One of them fits inside the other. Combine them and place the cover inside your AC socket. Smaller part (inner) should stay inside and bigger part (outer) should stay on the outside. Then use one of your plugs to rotate (as shown in photo with my hand in it) the inner part thus lock/unlock the socket. That means you don't have to take the cover out to use your outlet, yay! Important Note: When assembled, this part has 3mm thickness. That means 3mm in the way of your plugs. When you are using the cover, make sure plug fits tight in the socket! Consider avoiding plugging a high powered device to a socket with the cover. A problematic contact may cause serious issues, such as fire! Note: only compatible with European Schuko style outlets. Another note: This is not my original idea. There are commercial products very similar (probably better) to this.
